    {
        "id": "exerciseBox_cu9pe463zj",
        "question": "\\(\\text{Given $g(x) = x + 5$; Prove that $\\lim\\limits_{x~ \\to ~4} g(x) = 9$ using $\\epsilon - \\delta$} \\)",
        "answer": "To start, let's layout the inequalities for \\(\\delta\\) and \\(\\epsilon\\).\n$$\\lvert x - 4 \\rvert \\lt \\delta \\quad \\text{and} \\quad \\lvert g(x) - 9 \\rvert \\lt \\epsilon$$\nNow, let's try and make the inequality for \\(\\epsilon\\) resemble the inequality for \\(\\delta\\).\n\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n\\lvert g(x) - 9\\rvert &\\lt \\epsilon \\\\\n\\lvert (x + 5) - 9 \\rvert &\\lt \\epsilon\\\\\n\\lvert x - 4\\rvert &\\lt \\epsilon\\\\\n\\end{aligned}\n$$\n\nSo, we end up with the inequality \\( \\lvert x - 4\\rvert \\lt \\epsilon \\). We then declare that \\(\\delta = \\epsilon\\) and all that is left is to verify our claim.\n\nTo verify,\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n\\lvert x - 4\\rvert &\\lt \\delta \\\\\n\\lvert x - 4 \\rvert &\\lt \\epsilon\\\\\n\\lvert x + (5 - 9)\\rvert &\\lt \\epsilon && \\text{we can rewrite $4$ as $(5 - 9)$}\\\\\n\\lvert (x + 5) - 9 \\rvert &\\lt \\epsilon \\\\\n\\lvert g(x) - 9 \\rvert &\\lt \\epsilon && \\text{$\\square$}\n\\end{aligned}\n$$\n",
        "exerciseIndex": 4,
        "chartList": []
    },
    {
        "id": "exerciseBox_ino09qjg7w",
        "question": "\\(\\text{Given $h(x) = 4x^2 + 1$; Prove that $\\lim\\limits_{x~ \\to ~3} h(x) = 37$} \\)",
        "answer": "\nTo start, let's layout the inequalities for \\(\\delta\\) and \\(\\epsilon\\).\n$$\\lvert x - 3 \\rvert \\lt \\delta \\quad \\text{and} \\quad \\lvert h(x) - 37 \\rvert \\lt \\epsilon$$\nNow, let's try and make the inequality for \\(\\epsilon\\) resemble the inequality for \\(\\delta\\).\n\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n\\lvert h(x) - 37 \\rvert &\\lt \\epsilon\\\\\n\\lvert (4x^2 + 1) - 37 \\rvert &\\lt \\epsilon\\\\\n\\lvert 4x^2 - 36 \\rvert &\\lt \\epsilon\\\\\n4~\\lvert x^2 - 9 \\rvert &\\lt \\epsilon\\\\\n4~\\lvert (x - 3)(x + 3) \\rvert &\\lt \\epsilon\\\\\n4~\\lvert x + 3\\rvert  ~\\lvert x - 3 \\rvert &\\lt \\epsilon\\\\\n\\lvert x - 3 \\rvert &\\lt \\frac{\\epsilon}{4~\\lvert x + 3\\rvert }\\\\\n\\end{aligned}\n$$\n\nSeeing that the right side of the inquality contains an \\(x\\) variable, we can't use it for \\(\\delta\\) because \\(\\delta\\) is supposed to be a function of \\(\\epsilon\\) only. If we were to allow \\(\\delta\\) to be dependent on both \\(\\epsilon\\) and \\(x\\), then we could have scenario's where \\(\\lvert x - 3 \\rvert \\lt \\frac{\\epsilon}{4~\\lvert (x + 3)\\rvert }\\) does not hold true for every \\(\\epsilon \\gt 0\\).\n\nFor example, if we set \\(\\epsilon\\) to be \\(0.001\\) and \\(x\\) to be relatively close to \\(3\\), say \\(x = 2.999\\), does the inequality still hold true ?\n\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n\\lvert x - 3 \\rvert &\\lt \\delta \\\\\n\\lvert x - 3 \\rvert &\\lt \\frac{\\epsilon}{4~\\lvert x + 3\\rvert }\\\\\\\\\n\\lvert 2.999 - 3 \\rvert &\\lt \\frac{0.001}{4~\\lvert 2.999 + 3\\rvert }\\\\\\\\\n0.001 &\\not\\lt 0.00004167\n\\end{aligned}\n$$\n\nSo, our approach should be as follows, let's restrict the values for \\(\\delta\\) so that it satisfies the requirements of \\(\\epsilon\\) for every \\(\\epsilon \\gt 0 \\).\n\nTo start, let's note that we only really care about the values of \\(x\\) as they get closer and closer \\(3\\), so let's set an arbitrary upper bound of \\(1\\) on \\(\\delta\\) so that the distance between \\(x\\) and \\(3\\) is never greater than \\(1\\).\n\nWith that upper bound set, let's think about \\( \\lvert x - 3 \\rvert \\lt 1 \\) for a second. If \\( \\lvert x - 3 \\rvert \\lt 1 \\), then \\(2 \\lt x \\lt 4 \\).\n\nWe can then go one step further with \\(2 \\lt x \\lt 4 ~\\) to get \\(~5 \\lt x + 3 \\lt 7 \\). Now, we can use \\(~5 \\lt x + 3 \\lt 7 \\) to help us simplify \\(\\lvert x - 3 \\rvert \\lt \\frac{\\epsilon}{4~\\lvert x + 3\\rvert }\\).\n\nIf we are guaranteed that \\( x + 3 \\lt 7 \\), then we can claim \\(\\frac{\\epsilon}{4~\\lvert x + 3\\rvert } \\lt \\frac{\\epsilon}{4~\\lvert 7 \\rvert } = \\frac{\\epsilon}{28} \\). \n\nTaking a step back and seeing what we just did, we basically set an upper bound of \\(1\\) on \\(\\delta\\) and because of the upper bound, we now only care about the maximum value of \\(\\frac{\\epsilon}{4~\\lvert x + 3 \\rvert }\\), which we calculated to be \\(\\frac{\\epsilon}{28}\\)\n\nWe are almost there, we just need to verify our work.\n\nTo verify, we first set \\(\\delta = min\\{1, \\frac{\\epsilon}{28}\\}\\)\n\nIf \\(\\delta = 1\\) then \\(1 \\lt \\frac{\\epsilon}{28}\\) which means \\(\\epsilon \\gt 28\\):\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n\\lvert x - 3 \\rvert &\\lt \\delta \\\\\n\\lvert x - 3 \\rvert &\\lt 1 \\\\\n\\lvert x - 3 \\rvert \\cdot \\lvert x + 3 \\rvert &\\lt \\lvert x + 3 \\rvert \\lt  \\frac{\\epsilon}{28} && \\text{because $\\delta = 1$} \\\\\n\\lvert x^2 - 9\\rvert &\\lt \\lvert x + 3 \\rvert \\lt 7 && \\text{remember $~5 \\lt x + 3 \\lt 7$} \\\\\n4 \\cdot \\lvert x^2 - 9\\rvert &\\lt 4 \\cdot 7 \\\\\n\\lvert 4x^2 - 36\\rvert &\\lt 28 \\lt \\epsilon \\\\\n\\lvert 4x^2 + 1 - 37\\rvert &\\lt \\epsilon && \\text{we can rewrite $36$ as $(1 - 37)$}\\\\\n\\lvert f(x) - 37\\rvert &\\lt \\epsilon \\\\\n\\end{aligned}\n$$\n\nIf \\(\\delta = \\frac{\\epsilon}{28}\\):\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n\\lvert x - 3 \\rvert &\\lt \\delta \\\\\n\\lvert x - 3 \\rvert &\\lt \\frac{\\epsilon}{28} \\\\\n(x + 3) \\cdot \\lvert x - 3 \\rvert &\\lt 7 \\cdot \\frac{\\epsilon}{28} && \\text{remember $x + 3 \\lt 7$} \\\\\n\\lvert x^2 - 9\\rvert &\\lt \\frac{\\epsilon}{4} \\\\\n4 \\cdot \\lvert x^2 - 9\\rvert &\\lt \\epsilon \\\\\n\\lvert 4x^2 - 36\\rvert &\\lt \\epsilon \\\\\n\\lvert 4x^2 + 1 - 37\\rvert &\\lt \\epsilon && \\text{we can rewrite $36$ as $(1 - 37)$}\\\\\n\\lvert f(x) - 37\\rvert &\\lt \\epsilon && \\text{$\\square$} \\\\\n\\end{aligned}\n$$",
